    antiCheatingFlags: { flagged: false, similarityScore: 0 },
    ocrContent: `Student: Priya Nair  |  Roll No: 2024BBA-041  |  Paper ID: ECO-041

Q1. Define Keynesian Economics:
Keynesian economics holds that aggregate demand is the primary determinant of economic output in the short run. When private sector demand falls, as in a recession, government expenditure can compensate by increasing total demand. This is the basis of counter-cyclical fiscal policy — spending more during downturns and consolidating during booms.

Q2. Explain the Law of Diminishing Returns:
The Law of Diminishing Returns states that when one factor of production increases while all others remain fixed, the additional output generated per unit of the variable factor will eventually fall. I applied this to a textile factory: hiring 10 more workers on a fixed loom setup initially doubled throughput, but by the 15th worker the increase was marginal because the looms were already at full utilisation. The critical variable is the ceteris paribus condition on the fixed factors.

Q3. What is Price Elasticity of Demand?
PED = percentage change in quantity demanded / percentage change in price. If PED > 1, demand is elastic; if < 1, it is inelastic. Demand is typically more elastic when there are close substitutes, when the good is a luxury, or when consumers have more time to adjust. For example, petrol is inelastic in the short run but more elastic over 6 months as consumers switch to alternatives.

Q4. Explain Monetary Policy Mechanisms:
The Reserve Bank of India conducts monetary policy through the Monetary Policy Committee. Primary tools include the repo rate (rate at which banks borrow from RBI), reverse repo rate (rate RBI borrows from banks), CRR, SLR, and open market operations. A rate increase reduces lending and controls demand-pull inflation.`,
