    ocrContent: `Student: Anjali Das  |  Roll No: 2024BBA-055  |  Paper ID: ECO-055

Q1. Define Keynesian Economics:
Keynesian economics is a macroeconomic theory that posits effective demand — the total planned expenditure in an economy — drives output, income, and employment. During the Great Depression, Keynes observed that markets could get stuck in equilibrium with high unemployment, contradicting classical theory. His solution: government spending acts as a multiplier, injecting demand that circulates through the economy and generates income multiple times its original value.

Q2. Explain the Law of Diminishing Returns:
The Law of Diminishing Returns is a short-run production principle stating that as successive units of a variable input are added to fixed inputs, beyond some point the marginal product of the variable input will decrease. Example: a bakery with two ovens adds bakers — the 1st baker doubles output, the 5th baker adds 40% more, but the 9th baker adds only 5% because the ovens are already running at capacity. Ceteris paribus is the critical assumption.

Q3. What is Price Elasticity of Demand?
PED measures consumer responsiveness to price changes. PED = %ΔQd / %ΔP. A value of –2 means a 10% price rise leads to a 20% fall in demand (elastic). Determinants include: (1) availability of substitutes, (2) proportion of income spent, (3) necessity vs. luxury, (4) time horizon for adjustment. In the Indian context, onion prices are a classic example of inelastic staple demand.

Q4. Explain Monetary Policy Mechanisms:
The RBI uses six instruments: (1) Repo Rate, (2) Reverse Repo Rate, (3) CRR, (4) SLR, (5) Open Market Operations, (6) Market Stabilisation Scheme. Expansionary policy lowers repo rates to stimulate borrowing. Contractionary policy raises rates to control inflation. During COVID-19, the RBI cut the repo rate from 5.15% to 4.00% to support economic recovery.`,
